60% of young people in Sierra Leone are unemployed or underemployed. Many had their education disrupted by civil war. Lack of appropriate skills in the labour force slows the country's development and high quality, affordable vocational training is not readily available in Freetown. This project trains young men and women in life skills and vocational courses matched to employer demand. It offers business training and mentorship to young entrepreneurs, facilitates work placements and employment by making connections with companies, and raises revenue by charging firms for recruitment and in-house employee training. The project also helps young people improve their livelihoods and creates a better environment for employment.

7.2% of Uganda’s population is living with HIV and the rate has been rising since 2006. People with HIV still experience stigma and this marginalisation is one of the main reasons they are not able to access services. This project strengthens and expands the work of two community-based organisations, establishing and supporting a wider network of support groups of people living with HIV. There are close links with government clinics to improve the quality and availability of HIV services. It also helps establish village savings and loan schemes and helps create and strengthen opportunities for project beneficiaries to make a living. The project aims to improve the lives of people living with HIV, and make them more accepted in their communities.

AbleChildAfrica has been working for 4 years now with a wider remit than the former USDC UK - supporting a range of partners working on innovative solutions to change the lives of disabled children in Africa. Our 2007-2012 strategy has seen us achieving our goal of developing five partnerships accross 3 countries and finding a way to develop a positive approach to partnership with organisations working with disabled children and youth. We are coming to the end of our intial five year strategy and would like this grant to support the development of our next strategic plan consolidating what has been achieved to date and capitalising on our core mission going forward. In addition we would like support in two areas which we think will be key in that strategy - 1. the development of a well considered mechanism through which we can support mainstream development providers working with children to make their programmes and organisations inclusive and 2. the strengthening of our partnership network enabling it to grow and develop cross-network learning which we believe has significant benefits but which is difficult to fund from other sources.

Access to safe, adequate and affordable water is a real challenge for people living in slums. Privately-owned boreholes can be an important supply of water but their regulation is not enforced. Recent research has found the quality of water at boreholes in three of Nairobi’s slums to be dangerously poor, containing high levels of harmful bacteria and e-coli. Also that good hygiene practice is uncommon. As a result, local people suffer, and can even die from, diseases such as typhoid fever, diarrhoea and cholera. This project aims to promote safe drinking water and encourage a more sustainable approach to water provision and hygiene. Rather than building new boreholes, the project will make existing boreholes more efficient, cost-effective and safer. Training will be provided so that facilities can be maintained. There will also be hygiene promotion in schools and the community. As a result, people in the slums will be able to source clean water more cheaply and there will be a reduction in water-related diseases contributing to better health and school attendance.

According to UNESCO, under two-thirds of adults in Malawi can read. This project aims to improve children's literacy and numeracy skills in the infant years of primary school in Malawi. Every week, children are taken through a number of topics linked to the curriculum. Teachers are trained to support this work and adapt their own teaching practice in the classroom. Small classrooms are built for each school, allowing smaller classes. This work has demonstrated significant gain in an eight week period for some children.

Across Africa, HIV and AIDS affects millions of people, leaving many children orphaned and vulnerable. Yet parents and carers can find it hard to discuss HIV with young children and there are high levels of stigma and ignorance surrounding HIV. ‘Stepping Stones’ is a proven training package used in over 100 countries and available in 25 languages. It helps adults and young people explore how relations between men and women and other issues influence the way people behave, and how behaviour can be improved. In this project, The Salamander Trust is developing, for the first time, ‘Stepping Stones with Children’. This training package will help people to develop the skills to relate to younger children aged 5-14 on issues like death, disclosure of HIV status, stigma and age-appropriate information on HIV and sex. ‘Stepping Stones with Children’ will give children, their families and those caring for them, the materials and skills to better relate to each other on sensitive and difficult issues.

Across Africa women continue to face discrimination and marginalisation. They often experience gender-based violence, poor access to healthcare, and high rates of maternal and infant mortality. A key reason these challenges have persisted is leadership of women’s organisations, business and government has been weak. This project introduces an innovative, long-term approach that strengthens the leadership skills of both individuals and organisations. This way, women and their organisations can secure and protect their rights, increase the access they have to services, and also gain a greater opportunity to represent their interests.

Adama is a railway transit town with a population of 127,842 (7-18 population is 63,352) of which over 2000 are children living off on/the the streets. The railway is a big attraction for business opportunities and many people have fallen into the trap of chasing dreams which have resulted in poor livelihoods. Children have either been born or migrated to this place in search of opportunities and many are living tough lives eking a living as porters, casual workers, sex workers simply living on the streets. The rights of these children are trampled upon every day and they have limited safety nets. This application will undertake a research into the context of the street children in the country and Adama in particular, the extent of the problem, the nature of the problem, the available opportunities for addressing the problems. It will map out existing services and identify the key stakeholders. The result will be a greater understanding of the situation of street children in Adama, the opportunities there are to address any identified issues, and design of appropriate interventions. Implementation of follow-on programmes should ensure the upholding of the rights of street children, and ensuring a brighter future for them.

A detailed education needs assessment will be undertaken in the Gedo region of Somalia.This is 2nd largest region in the country with a population made up of nomadic & pastoralist communities. Somalia has one of the lowest enrollment rates in education with only 42% children in school. Low numbers of qualified teachers, in particular female teachers, exacerbate the challenges in education provision. Very little education provision is available across all 7 districts in the region.The needs assessment will understand the current situation of primary & secondary schools, the physical state of schools, rationale for drop out & non attendance, the quality of education & ways to improve provision

20,000 girls and boys, many accused of being witches, are living on the streets of the Democratic Republic of Congo. Every day they face the risk of abuse, drug-addiction and violence. This project helps find street children and encourages them to visit a drop-in centre. Here staff offer medical care, a meal, washing facilities, games and classes to teach them to read and write. There is a temporary shelter for girls. It helps the children go back to school or train to get a job. The project finds their families and helps them with their problems so the children can return home. Staff visit families regularly, offering them small loans to start small businesses and help with their rent. The project broadcasts radio programmes and organises meetings with local church leaders, government authorities and the community, to tackle people’s attitudes towards the children, especially the belief in child witchcraft.
